r's \"Refactoring UI\" and its design principles:\n\n## Overview\n\nRefactoring UI is a book, video series, and a collection of resources created by Steve Schoger and Adam Wathan that teaches everything they know about designing for the web, packed into a single comprehensive resource.\n\n## Key Design Principles\n\nThe book teaches how to design beautiful user interfaces using specific tactics explained from a developer's point-of-view. Some of the core principles include:\n\n1. **Whitespace**: Avoid clutter by using generous spacing between elements, as ample padding around buttons and text improves readability and reduces visual fatigue.\n\n2. **Visual Hierarchy**: Guide users' attention by using size, color, and placement to emphasize important elements, which prevents confusion and directs users towards desired actions.\n\n3. **Color and Typography**: Choose colors that complement each other and align with your brand identity to create a cohesive and visually pleasing experience.\n\n4. **Typography**: Ensure text is easily legible, especially on smaller screens, as larger fonts improve readability and reduce eye strain.\n\n## Current Relevance (2024-2025)\n\nRefactoring UI remains the most recommended book for both beginner and experienced designers and is one of the most practical and valuable resources for anyone working on UI design or development.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"70835761-a34b-4801-8a88-55516a24fc7b","timestamp":"2026-02-08T18:43:57.036Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"3f695660-c469-4fb7-bd01-b503ca5fb447"}
{"parentUuid":"86cb12f8-a582-403b-b4aa-d5094df09cd5","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/jwilger/projects/todo_list","sessionId":"2ac9b335-ecf3-4e43-a8c4-e750faf9e881","version":"2.1.37","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"affc159","slug":"cached-toasting-simon","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01M6gKYMR1qVabF2CNrKxy1a","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Steve Krug \"Don't Make Me Think\" usability philosophy\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Don't Make Me Think - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don't_Make_Me_Think\"},{\"title\":\"Don't Make Me Think: A Common Sense Approach to Web Usability, 2nd Edition: Krug, Steve: 8601404639708: Amazon.com: Books\",\"url\":\"https://www.amazon.com/Dont-Make-Me-Think-Usability/dp/0321344758\"},{\"title\":\"Don't Make Me Think, Revisited: A Common Sense Approach to Web Usability (3rd Edition) (Voices That Matter): Krug, Steve: 9780321965516: Amazon.com: Books\",\"url\":\"https://www.amazon.com/Dont-Make-Think-Revisited-Usability/dp/0321965515\"},{\"title\":\"Don't Make Me Think, Revisited: A Common Sense Approach to Web Usability by Steve Krug | Goodreads\",\"url\":\"https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18197267-don-t-make-me-think-revisited\"},{\"title\":\"Don't Make Me Think by Steve Krug – The Rabbit Hole\",\"url\":\"https://blas.com/dont-make-me-think/\"},{\"title\":\"Don't Make Me Think: 20 Thoughts on Usability by Steve Krug.\",\"url\":\"https://blog.tubikstudio.com/dont-make-me-think-20-thoughts-on-usability-by-steve-krug/\"},{\"title\":\"UX Design Insights From Don't Make Me Think By Steve Krug\",\"url\":\"https://www.ronins.co.uk/hub/dont-make-me-think-by-steve-krug/\"},{\"title\":\"Book Summary - Don't Make Me Think, Revisited (Steve ...\",\"url\":\"https://readingraphics.com/book-summary-dont-make-me-think/\"},{\"title\":\"Don't Make Me Think, Revisited\",\"url\":\"https://dn790002.ca.archive.org/0/items/SteveKrugDontMakeMeThink/Steve_Krug_Don%E2%80%99t_Make_Me_Think,.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Don't make me think, revisited : a common sense approach to Web usability : Krug, Steve, author : Free Download, Borrow, and Streaming : Internet Archive\",\"url\":\"https://archive.org/details/dontmakemethinkr0000krug\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Steve Krug's \"Don't Make Me Think\" usability philosophy:\n\n## Overview\n\n\"Don't Make Me Think\" is a book by Steve Krug about human–computer interaction and web usability. Originally published in 2000, the book was revised in 2005, and again 2013 to add a section about mobile UX, and has sold more than 700,000 copies.\n\n## Core Philosophy\n\nThe book's premise is that a good software program or web site should let users accomplish their intended tasks as easily and directly as possible. Krug points out that people are good at satisficing, or taking the first available solution to their problem, so design should take advantage of this.\n\n## Key Principles\n\nSteve Krug's Laws of Usability—First Law: Don't make me think. Make things obvious and self-evident, or at least self-explanatory. Additional principles include:\n\n- People scan; they don't read. People choose the first reasonable option.\n- Every question mark adds to our cognitive workload, distracting our attention from the task at hand.\n- The rule of thumb might be something like \"three mindless, unambiguous clicks equal one click that requires thought.\"\n\n## Focus on People Over Technology\n\nUsability is about people and how they understand and use things, not about technology.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"8ea41a38-5584-4272-b2f7-21b835e18d41","timestamp":"2026-02-08T18:43:57.449Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"86cb12f8-a582-403b-b4aa-d5094df09cd5"}
{"parentUuid":"fd7fe197-7f42-4872-8ff1-00aec7c62d6f","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/jwilger/projects/todo_list","sessionId":"2ac9b335-ecf3-4e43-a8c4-e750faf9e881","version":"2.1.37","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"affc159","slug":"cached-toasting-simon","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018GWHRtebg4f8x4jR94pEdn","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Carson Gross HTMX \"Hypermedia Systems\" philosophy 2024 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Hypermedia Systems: Gross, Carson, Stepinski, Adam, Akşimşek, Deniz, Talcott, William, Amundsen, Mike: 9798394025143: Amazon.com: Books\",\"url\":\"https://www.amazon.com/Hypermedia-Systems-Carson-Gross/dp/B0C9S88QV6\"},{\"title\":\"Hypermedia Systems By Carson Gross\",\"url\":\"https://www.bennadel.com/blog/4769-hypermedia-systems-by-carson-gross.htm\"},{\"title\":\"Hypermedia Systems by Carson Gross | Goodreads\",\"url\":\"https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/192405005-hypermedia-systems\"},{\"title\":\"SE Radio 671: Carson Gross on HTMX – Software Engineering Radio\",\"url\":\"https://se-radio.net/2025/06/se-radio-671-carson-gross-on-htmx/\"},{\"title\":\"htmx ~ The future of htmx\",\"url\":\"https://htmx.org/essays/future/\"},{\"title\":\"Carson Gross (Creator of HTMX) Reflects on Hypermedia Systems\",\"url\":\"https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/carson-gross-creator-of-htmx-reflects-on-hypermedia/id1745257325?i=1000697529001\"},{\"title\":\"PodRocket: HTMX in 2025 with Carson Gross\",\"url\":\"https://podrocket.logrocket.com/htmx-in-2025-carson-gross\"},{\"title\":\"HTMX in 2025 with Carson Gross - PodRocket - A web development podcast from LogRocket | iHeart\",\"url\":\"https://www.iheart.com/podcast/269-podrocket-a-web-developmen-74819408/episode/htmx-in-2025-with-carson-gross-273860979/\"},{\"title\":\"Carson Gross (Creator of HTMX) Reflects on Hypermedia Systems by Book Overflow\",\"url\":\"https://creators.spotify.com/pod/profile/bookoverflow/episodes/Carson-Gross-Creator-of-HTMX-Reflects-on-Hypermedia-Systems-e2vlq26\"},{\"title\":\"Hypermedia Systems 1, Gross, Carson, Stepinski, Adam, Akşimşek , Deniz, Talcott, William, Amundsen, Mike, eBook - Amazon.com\",\"url\":\"https://www.amazon.com/Hypermedia-Systems-Carson-Gross-ebook/dp/B0CC315VJK\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Carson Gross, HTMX, and his \"Hypermedia Systems\" philosophy:\n\n## About Carson Gross and HTMX\n\nCarson Gross is the creator of a JavaScript framework called htmx. HTMX—or, \"hypertext markup extensions\"—provides an attributes-based approach for adding rich interactivity to your web application.\n\n## Hypermedia Systems Philosophy\n\nThe \"Hypermedia Systems\" book explores a simpler approach to building applications on the Web and beyond with htmx and Hyperview, two technologies that embrace hypermedia as a system architecture.\n\nThe entire first section of the book covers the history of the web, the concept of hypermedia as a unified interface, the true and original meaning of REST (REpresentational State Transfer), and makes the argument that HTML and HATEOS (Hypermedia as the Engine of Application State) has many advantages over the extremely tight coupling required by today's Single-Page Application (SPA) frameworks.\n\n## Core Philosophy of HTMX\n\nThe core philosophy of \"HTML as the interface\" and how hypermedia principles influenced HTMX's design is central to his work. Any element can issue any type of request in response to any event, and it can place the response content anywhere in the DOM, which Gross says completes HTML as a hypermedia.\n\n## Recent Activity (2024-2025)\n\nCarson Gross and Alex Petros discuss htmx's future direction and philosophy, explaining how the project aims to emulate jQuery's success through API stability, minimal feature additions, and quarterly releases while continuing to promote hypermedia-driven development. Carson Gross talks about its evolution from intercooler.js, its viral rise on social media, and its philosophy of simplicity and stability.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"227143e7-fa99-465a-82e8-2de1dd89706d","timestamp":"2026-02-08T18:43:58.335Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"fd7fe197-7f42-4872-8ff1-00aec7c62d6f"}
