nd \"vibe coding\" concept on Substack in 2025:\n\n## Communication Style & Personality\n\nKent Beck is a \"boomer geek\" who stopped having patience for minutiae about 20 years ago. His communication style appears enthusiastic and exploratory. He shares his thoughts on Substack \"raw & unfiltered for feedback\" with paying subscribers, and he describes himself as being excited about the \"world of possibilities\" that are \"opening up\".\n\n## \"Vibe Coding\" vs. \"Augmented Coding\"\n\nBeck prefers the term \"augmented coding\" over \"vibe coding.\" He thinks the term \"vibe coding\" is \"fantastic\" as \"a concept that needed to be named\", but notes the problem is \"it just sounds like you're rolling a fat one and sitting in a hot tub,\" so he \"prefer[s] to think of it as augmented coding\".\n\nThe distinction is significant: Vibe coding treats AI as a magic solution generator where you describe what you want and hope for working code, caring only about system behavior, not code quality. Augmented coding maintains traditional software engineering standards while leveraging AI capabilities, with care about code complexity, test coverage, and maintainability.\n\n## Substack Activity in 2025\n\nBeck has been doing \"vibe coding\" (which he calls \"augmented coding\") and posting about it on social media. He regularly shares insights about augmented coding on his Tidy First newsletter, and his main business is his newsletter at tidyfirst.substack.com, where he writes about software design, augmented coding experiences, personal growth, and incentive systems.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"8a16c4f1-ea33-40df-b547-22f09f75196e","timestamp":"2026-02-08T18:44:10.254Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"59b9226f-88c0-4997-8c14-65a5b6d6990c"}
