{"parentUuid":"db8306a0-e7eb-4756-922e-2ef43bad4a70","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/jwilger/projects/todo_list","sessionId":"2ac9b335-ecf3-4e43-a8c4-e750faf9e881","version":"2.1.37","gitBranch":"main","agentId":"affc159","slug":"cached-toasting-simon","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AvQya6zmcrxQhrppUoGuxV","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Carson Gross HTMX 2.0 philosophy simplicity REST hypermedia approach SPA criticism\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"SE Radio 671: Carson Gross on HTMX – Software Engineering Radio\",\"url\":\"https://se-radio.net/2025/06/se-radio-671-carson-gross-on-htmx/\"},{\"title\":\"Hypermedia Systems By Carson Gross\",\"url\":\"https://www.bennadel.com/blog/4769-hypermedia-systems-by-carson-gross.htm\"},{\"title\":\"Complexity bad: An interview with HTMX creator Carson Gross | InfoWorld\",\"url\":\"https://www.infoworld.com/article/2336201/complexity-bad-an-interview-with-carson-gross.html\"},{\"title\":\"Hypermedia Systems by Carson Gross | Goodreads\",\"url\":\"https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/192405005-hypermedia-systems\"},{\"title\":\"Book Review — Hypermedia Systems\",\"url\":\"https://acritelli.medium.com/book-review-hypermedia-systems-65a9379767cf\"},{\"title\":\"htmx ~ Hypermedia-Driven Applications\",\"url\":\"https://htmx.org/essays/hypermedia-driven-applications/\"},{\"title\":\"The CEO of htmx likes codin' dirty featuring Carson Gross (Changelog Interviews #646)\",\"url\":\"https://changelog.com/podcast/646\"},{\"title\":\"Hypermedia Systems: Gross, Carson, Stepinski, Adam, Akşimşek, Deniz, Talcott, William, Amundsen, Mike: 9798394025143: Amazon.com: Books\",\"url\":\"https://www.amazon.com/Hypermedia-Systems-Carson-Gross/dp/B0C9S88QV6\"},{\"title\":\"Carson Gross (Creator of HTMX) Reflects on Hypermedia Systems\",\"url\":\"https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/carson-gross-creator-of-htmx-reflects-on-hypermedia/id1745257325?i=1000697529001\"},{\"title\":\"htmx ~ A Response To \\\"Have Single-Page Apps Ruined the Web?\\\"\",\"url\":\"https://htmx.org/essays/a-response-to-rich-harris/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what Carson Gross has articulated about HTMX's philosophy and approach:\n\n## Core Philosophy: Simplicity and Hypermedia\n\nCarson explains the core philosophy of \"HTML as the interface\" and how hypermedia principles influenced HTMX's design. He emphasizes that \"simplicity, what makes something fast being simple.\" This philosophy extends beyond just the technical implementation to a broader worldview about software development.\n\n## The Hypermedia-Driven Application (HDA) Approach\n\nThe Hypermedia Driven Application (HDA) architecture is a new/old approach to building web applications that combines the simplicity & flexibility of traditional Multi-Page Applications (MPAs) with the better user experience of Single-Page Applications (SPAs). An HDA uses declarative, HTML-embedded syntax rather than imperative scripting, and interacts with the server in terms of hypermedia (HTML) rather than non-hypermedia formats like JSON, thereby staying within the original REST-ful architecture of the web in a way that the SPA architecture does not.\n\n## State Complexity and REST Principles\n\nGross argues that \"the biggest thing is you're reducing the amount of state that you've got in the total system,\" because RPC systems require server state, client-side state stores, and the DOM to all remain in sync, which is complicated. HTMX tries to build on the network architecture by enhancing HTML as hypermedia, rather than replacing that original architecture with a new one, namely fixed-format JSON Data APIs.\n\n## Criticism of SPAs\n\nHe observes that JavaScript developers immersed in engineering culture of front end frameworks find the current complexity natural, but for many others, the JavaScript ecosystem is simply insanely overly-complicated and comically so, given the requirements of most web applications. Gross expresses frustration with SPAs in unstable network conditions, noting he's \"seen plenty of spinners in single page applications.\"\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"0a5a9883-a226-4fe8-a0e5-53be592bb1d5","timestamp":"2026-02-08T18:44:14.767Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"db8306a0-e7eb-4756-922e-2ef43bad4a70"}
